#compdef hidi
# ============================================================================
# hidi - flexible HID to MIDI translation layer
#         turns USB HID devices (keyboards,
#         gamepads, mice, joysticks) into MIDI
#         controllers (Go, GPL-3.0)
#
# Author : gethiox + contributors
# Upstream: https://github.com/gethiox/HIDI
#
# `hidi` is a Linux daemon that intercepts events
# from USB HID input devices (keyboards, gamepads,
# joysticks, mice) via the kernel's evdev
# interface, applies per-device-class mapping
# configurations, and emits MIDI messages to a
# configurable ALSA MIDI output (or a virtual
# ALSA MIDI port). This enables turning any HID
# device into a MIDI controller for music
# production / live performance / DAW automation.
#
# Use cases:
#   - Convert a regular USB keyboard into a piano
#     keyboard with key-to-note mapping
#   - Use an Xbox/PlayStation gamepad as a MIDI
#     controller (analog sticks → CC values; face
#     buttons → notes; D-pad → octave shifts)
#   - Foot-pedal HID devices for sustain/expression
#     pedal emulation
#   - Gaming-mouse extra buttons → MIDI Program
#     Change for live preset cycling
#   - Build a custom DIY MIDI controller from
#     scrap USB hardware
#
# Configuration is per-device-class via TOML
# files in $HIDI_CONFIG_DIR / `~/.config/hidi/`
# specifying:
#   - Key/button → MIDI note mapping
#   - Analog axis → MIDI CC mapping
#   - Per-device octave + channel + transposition
#   - OpenRGB LED feedback for compatible
#     keyboards (per-key color change based on
#     note state)
#   - Action triggers (octave up/down, channel
#     change, sustain pedal toggle)
#
# Usage:
#   hidi [flags]
#
# Flags (Go stdlib `flag` package; single-dash
# style):
#   -profile                       - run pprof
#                                     web server
#                                     at
#                                     0.0.0.0:8080
#                                     for
#                                     performance
#                                     profiling
#   -grab                          - grab input
#                                     devices for
#                                     exclusive
#                                     usage
#                                     (prevents
#                                     them from
#                                     reaching X/
#                                     Wayland +
#                                     standard
#                                     input)
#   -openrgb                       - enable
#                                     OpenRGB
#                                     support for
#                                     LED
#                                     feedback on
#                                     compatible
#                                     keyboards
#   -nocolor                       - disable ANSI
#                                     color in
#                                     stdout
#                                     output
#   -loglevel <n>                  - logging
#                                     verbosity
#                                     level (0-4;
#                                     default 3)
#                                     0: general
#                                     info
#                                     1: action
#                                     events
#                                     2: key
#                                     events
#                                     3: unassigned
#                                     key events
#                                     4: analog
#                                     events
#   -nopony                        - disable ASCII
#                                     pony art
#                                     (pony.txt is
#                                     embedded as
#                                     easter egg)
#   -mididevice <n>                - select N-th
#                                     MIDI device
#                                     (default 0,
#                                     i.e. first)
#   -orgbport <n>                  - external
#                                     OpenRGB
#                                     server port
#                                     (default
#                                     -1, use
#                                     embedded)
#   -listmididevices               - list
#                                     available
#                                     MIDI
#                                     devices +
#                                     exit
#   -listdevices                   - list
#                                     available
#                                     HID input
#                                     devices
#                                     (keyboards/
#                                     gamepads/
#                                     joysticks)
#                                     + exit
#   -silent                        - no output
#                                     logging
#                                     (best
#                                     performance)
#   -virtual                       - create
#                                     virtual
#                                     ALSA MIDI
#                                     port
#                                     instead of
#                                     connecting
#                                     to existing
#                                     one
#   -standalone                    - preserve
#                                     selected
#                                     keyboard
#                                     as standard
#                                     input
#                                     device
#                                     (don't grab
#                                     it
#                                     exclusively)
#
# Example invocation:
#   hidi -listdevices
#   hidi -listmididevices
#   hidi -mididevice 1 -grab -openrgb
#   hidi -virtual -loglevel 4 -profile
#
# The gomidi lane is built on `gitlab.com/gomidi/
# midi/v2 v2.0.23` (declared verbatim at upstream
# go.mod HEAD as a direct dep, imported as
# `gomidi "gitlab.com/gomidi/midi/v2"` in cmd/
# hidi/main.go line 26, used throughout internal/
# pkg/midi/driver/alsa for ALSA MIDI device
# enumeration + MIDI message construction +
# real-time MIDI message transmission), the
# canonical Go MIDI library by Marc Rene Arns
# (gomidi org) - gitlab.com/gomidi/midi.
#
# Marc Rene Arns's gomidi/midi is the de-facto
# canonical Go MIDI library:
#   - Cross-platform MIDI I/O (Linux ALSA via
#     `alsa` driver subpackage + macOS CoreMIDI +
#     Windows WinMM)
#   - Multi-version codebase (v1 + v2 with
#     improved API + bug fixes)
#   - Strongly-typed MIDI message construction
#     (rather than raw byte arrays)
#   - High-level abstractions for MIDI clock +
#     SMPTE + sysex + meta events
#   - SMF (Standard MIDI File) read/write
#     support
#   - GM (General MIDI) instrument constants
#   - MIDI track + tempo + time-signature
#     helpers
#   - Drivers separated into independent
#     subpackages (rtmidi C wrapper + portmidi
#     C wrapper + ALSA-direct pure-Go +
#     Windows pure-Go)
#
# gomidi's distinguishing position vs Go MIDI
# alternatives:
#   - gomidi/midi (Arns): canonical; multi-
#     driver; THIS AXIS
#   - rakyll/portmidi: Jaana Burcu Dogan
#     (rakyll)'s PortMIDI Go bindings; minimal +
#     cgo-dependent
#   - mdlayher/launchpad: Matt Layher's
#     specialized Novation Launchpad bindings
#     (uses gomidi underneath)
#
# Marc Rene Arns's broader Go ecosystem
# footprint (the gomidi org):
#   - gomidi/midi v1 + v2 (canonical Go MIDI;
#     THIS AXIS)
#   - gomidi/connect (MIDI connection abstraction
#     layer)
#   - gomidi/smf (Standard MIDI File reader/
#     writer)
#   - gomidi/mid (high-level MIDI controller
#     helpers)
#   - gomidi/sf2 (SoundFont 2 file reader)
#
# Arns's role in Go is *specialized music-
# protocol infrastructure* - similar to:
#   - Y. T. Chung (zonyitoo, Rust): rust-ini +
#     Shadowsocks + bson
#   - Patrick Klein (Boddlnagg, Rust): midir +
#     bindgen audio bindings
#
# Arns's position is unique in the Go ecosystem -
# while most foundational Go authors target
# web/storage/build infrastructure, Arns built
# an entire vertical for MIDI + music-software
# integration that's the de-facto canonical for
# Go-based DAW + sequencer + synthesizer
# development.
#
# hidi uses gomidi in internal/pkg/midi/driver/
# alsa to:
#   1. Enumerate available ALSA MIDI ports
#      (`gomidi.GetOutPorts()` + iteration)
#   2. Connect to a selected output port (`port.
#      Open()`)
#   3. Optionally create a virtual ALSA port
#      (`gomidi.NewVirtual(...)`) when -virtual
#      is set
#   4. Construct + send MIDI messages from HID
#      events (NoteOn + NoteOff + ControlChange
#      + ProgramChange + PitchBend)
#   5. Handle sysex messages for OpenRGB LED
#      feedback synchronization
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 269 :: MIDI (Musical Instrument Digital
#              Interface) device I/O libraries
#              (cross-platform MIDI 1.0 spec +
#              USB MIDI Class + sysex message
#              handling)
# Round 1506 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 269
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : Boddlnagg/midir            [R1505 _flow-8-midi]
#             (Patrick Klein; canonical
#              Rust MIDI; pure-Rust)
#   Go      : gomidi/midi                [R1506 THIS FILE]
#             (Marc Rene Arns; canonical
#              Go MIDI; multi-driver
#              with pure-Go ALSA +
#              cgo-wrapped rtmidi/
#              portmidi options)
#   TS/Node : justinlatimer/node-midi    [R1507 closing]
#             (Justin Latimer; rtmidi
#              wrapper via node-gyp)
#
# gomidi/midi is structurally interesting in
# this axis because it offers *multi-driver
# abstraction*:
#   - alsa (pure-Go Linux ALSA bindings; no
#     C dependency for Linux-only use cases)
#   - rtmidi (cgo wrapper for cross-platform
#     coverage including macOS + Windows)
#   - portmidi (cgo wrapper for an alternative
#     C library)
#   - webmidi (Web MIDI API for wasm)
#
# This driver-abstraction pattern is unique
# among the three axis canonicals - midir
# (Rust) does its own platform abstraction
# internally; node-midi (Node) wraps rtmidi
# only. gomidi lets the consumer choose the
# driver backend at compile time.
#
# Use-case spectrum across the lanes (so far):
#   - flow-8-midi (Rust, midir): cross-
#     platform desktop MIDI controller for the
#     Behringer FLOW 8 mixer
#   - hidi (Go, gomidi/midi): Linux HID-to-
#     MIDI translation daemon turning USB
#     keyboards/gamepads/joysticks into MIDI
#     controllers
#
# The Rust + Go contrast in this axis is
# illustrative:
#   - Rust (midir): single-canonical pure-Rust
#     library; no driver choice
#   - Go (gomidi): multi-driver framework with
#     pluggable backends; pure-Go ALSA + cgo
#     options for non-Linux
#
# Both achieve canonical-library status in their
# respective ecosystems but via different
# architectural choices reflecting language
# culture:
#   - Rust: prefer pure-language single
#     implementation
#   - Go: prefer multi-driver abstraction with
#     opt-in cgo
#
# Multi-axis canonical-Go author cohort (now
# spanning 10 distinct individuals):
#   - Andrew Gerrand + Go team (stdlib)
#   - Russ Cox (Go modules + crypto)
#   - Gustavo Niemeyer (yaml.v3 + gopkg.in
#     infrastructure)
#   - Klaus Post (compress + reedsolomon +
#     cpuid + asmfmt)
#   - Sergey Kamardin (gobwas/glob + gobwas/ws +
#     gobwas/httphead + gobwas/pool)
#   - Anthony Starks (ajstarks/svgo + deck +
#     dchart + openvg + gensvg)
#   - Jeevanandam Madanagopal (go-resty +
#     go-aah + go-model + sslmate-go)
#   - Matt Holt (Caddy + CertMagic + archives +
#     timeliner + acmez)
#   - Joe Chen / Unknwon (go-ini + Macaron +
#     Gogs + com)
#   - Marc Rene Arns / gomidi org (gomidi/midi +
#     connect + smf + mid + sf2, THIS AXIS)
#
# Arns is the first author in the Go cohort
# whose foundational position is in the music-
# software vertical. Each of the 10 Go canonical
# authors occupies a distinct vertical:
#   - Stdlib: format/protocol baseline
#   - Cox: build system + crypto
#   - Niemeyer: YAML + gopkg versioning
#     infrastructure
#   - Post: SIMD-accelerated systems
#   - Kamardin: specialized network protocols
#   - Starks: vector graphics + visualization
#   - Madanagopal: HTTP client ergonomics
#   - Holt: web server + HTTPS automation
#   - Chen: Git-service + Chinese-language
#     web frameworks
#   - Arns: MIDI + music-software (THIS AXIS)
# ============================================================================

_hidi() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '-profile[run pprof web server at 0.0.0.0:8080]' \
        '-grab[grab input devices for exclusive usage]' \
        '-openrgb[enable OpenRGB LED feedback support]' \
        '-nocolor[disable ANSI color in stdout]' \
        '-loglevel=[logging verbosity level (0-4)]:n:(0 1 2 3 4)' \
        '-nopony[disable ASCII pony art]' \
        '-mididevice=[select N-th MIDI device]:n:' \
        '-orgbport=[external OpenRGB server port]:port:' \
        '-listmididevices[list available MIDI devices and exit]' \
        '-listdevices[list available HID input devices and exit]' \
        '-silent[no output logging (best performance)]' \
        '-virtual[create virtual ALSA MIDI port]' \
        '-standalone[preserve selected keyboard as standard input device]' \
        '(- *)-h[print help]'
}

_hidi "$@"
